statement.p:
The 3-dimensional vectors

  \wvec_1 = \threevec1{-1}1,\hspace{24pt}
  \wvec_2 = \threevec1{1}0,\hspace{24pt}
  \wvec_3 = \threevec1{-1}{-2}.

form an orthogonal set, which can be verified by computing

  \begin{array}{rcl}
  \wvec_1\cdot\wvec_2 \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\
  \wvec_1\cdot\wvec_3 \amp {}={} \amp 0 \\
  \wvec_2\cdot\wvec_3 \amp {}={} \amp 0\text{.} \\
  \end{array}

Notice that this set of vectors forms a basis for
\real^3.

The vectors

  \wvec_1 = \fourvec1111,\hspace{24pt}
  \wvec_2 = \fourvec11{-1}{-1},\hspace{24pt}
  \wvec_3 = \fourvec1{-1}1{-1}

form an orthogonal set of 4-dimensional vectors.  Since there
are only three vectors, this set does not form a basis for
\real^4.  It does, however, form a basis for a
3-dimensional subspace W of \real^4.

subsection.p:
Using this proposition, we can see that an orthogonal set of vectors must be linearly independent. Suppose, for instance, that \wvec_1,\wvec_2,\ldots,\wvec_n is a set of nonzero orthogonal vectors and that one of the vectors is a linear combination of the others, say,
\wvec_3 = c_1\wvec_1 + c_2\wvec_2\text{.}
We therefore know that
\wvec_3 = \frac{\wvec_3\cdot\wvec_1}{\wvec_1\cdot\wvec_1}\wvec_1 + \frac{\wvec_3\cdot\wvec_2}{\wvec_2\cdot\wvec_2}\wvec_2 = \zerovec\text{,}
which cannot happen since we know that \wvec_3 is nonzero. This tells us that

li.p:
Since \len{\wvec_1} = \sqrt{3}, we find

  \uvec_1 = \frac{1}{\sqrt{3}}\wvec_1 =
  \threevec{1/\sqrt{3}}{-1/\sqrt{3}}{1/\sqrt{3}}

We find that

  \uvec_2 =
  \threevec{1/\sqrt{2}}{1/\sqrt{2}}0,\hspace{24pt}
  \uvec_3 =
  \threevec{1/\sqrt{6}}{-1/\sqrt{6}}{-2/\sqrt{6}}

We find that

  \uvec_2 =
  \threevec{1/\sqrt{2}}{1/\sqrt{2}}0,\hspace{24pt}
  \uvec_3 =
  \threevec{1/\sqrt{6}}{-1/\sqrt{6}}{-2/\sqrt{6}}

statement.p:
The vectors

  \uvec_1=\twovec{1/\sqrt{2}}{1/\sqrt{2}},\hspace{24pt}
  \uvec_2=\twovec{-1/\sqrt{2}}{1/\sqrt{2}}

are an orthonormal set of vectors in \real^2 and
form an orthonormal basis for \real^2.

If we form the matrix

  Q=\begin{bmatrix}
  \uvec_1 \amp \uvec_2
  \end{bmatrix}
  = \begin{bmatrix}
  1/\sqrt{2} \amp -1/\sqrt{2} \\
  1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{2} \\
  \end{bmatrix}\text{,}

we find that Q^TQ = I since  tells us that

  Q^TQ = \begin{bmatrix}
  \uvec_1\cdot\uvec_1 \amp \uvec_1\cdot\uvec_2 \\
  \uvec_2\cdot\uvec_1 \amp \uvec_2\cdot\uvec_2 \\
  \end{bmatrix}
  =
  \begin{bmatrix}
  1 \amp 0 \\
  0 \amp 1 \\
  \end{bmatrix}

subsection.p:
      If we have an orthonormal basis
      \uvec_1,\uvec_2,\ldots,\uvec_n for W, the
      projection formula simplifies to

	\bhat=
	(\bvec\cdot\uvec_1)~\uvec_1 + 
	(\bvec\cdot\uvec_2)~\uvec_2 +
	\cdots + 
	(\bvec\cdot\uvec_n)~\uvec_n\text{.}

      If we then form the matrix

	Q =
	\begin{bmatrix}
	\uvec_1 \amp \uvec_2 \amp \ldots \amp \uvec_n 
	\end{bmatrix}\text{,}

      this expression may be succintly written


	  \bhat \amp {}={}
	  (\bvec\cdot\uvec_1)~\uvec_1 + 
	  (\bvec\cdot\uvec_2)~\uvec_2 +
	  \cdots + 
	  (\bvec\cdot\uvec_n)~\uvec_n


	  \amp {}={}
	  \begin{bmatrix}
	  \uvec_1\amp\uvec_2\amp\ldots\amp\uvec_n
	  \end{bmatrix}
	  \begin{bmatrix}
	  \uvec_1\cdot\bvec \\
	  \uvec_2\cdot\bvec \\
	  \vdots \\
	  \uvec_n\cdot\bvec \\
	  \end{bmatrix}


	  \amp {}={} QQ^T\bvec

statement.p:
In the previous activity, we looked at the plane W
defined by the two orthogonal vectors

  \wvec_1=\threevec22{-1},\hspace{24pt}
  \wvec_2=\threevec102\text{.}

We can form an orthonormal basis by scalar multiplying these
vectors to have unit length:

  \uvec_1=\frac13\threevec22{-1} =
  \threevec{2/3}{2/3}{-1/3},\hspace{24pt}
  \uvec_2=\frac1{\sqrt{5}}\threevec102 =
  \threevec{1/\sqrt{5}}0{2/\sqrt{5}}\text{.}

Using these vectors, we form the matrix

  Q =
  \begin{bmatrix}
  2/3 \amp 1/\sqrt{5} \\
  2/3 \amp 0 \\
  -1/3 \amp 2/\sqrt{5} \\
  \end{bmatrix}\text{.}

The projection onto the plane W is then given by
the matrix

  QQ^T =
  \begin{bmatrix}
  2/3 \amp 1/\sqrt{5} \\
  2/3 \amp 0 \\
  -1/3 \amp 2/\sqrt{5} \\
  \end{bmatrix}
  \begin{bmatrix}
  2/3 \amp 2/3 \amp -1/3 \\
  1/\sqrt{5} \amp 0 \amp 2/\sqrt{5} \\
  \end{bmatrix}
  =
  \begin{bmatrix}
  {29}/{45} \amp {4}/{9} \amp {8}/{45} \\
  {4}/{9} \amp {4}/{9} \amp -{2}/{9} \\
  {8}/{45} \amp -{2}/{9} \amp {41}/{45}
  \end{bmatrix}\text{.}

Alternatively, we use the matrix QQ^T,
as in , to find that

  \bhat = QQ^T\bvec = 
  \begin{bmatrix}
  {29}/{45} \amp {4}/{9} \amp {8}/{45} \\
  {4}/{9} \amp {4}/{9} \amp -{2}/{9} \\
  {8}/{45} \amp -{2}/{9} \amp {41}/{45}
  \end{bmatrix}\threevec100
  =
  \cthreevec{{29}/{45}}{4/9}{8/{45}}\text{.}

li.p:
Q^TQ = \begin{bmatrix}
1 \amp 0 \\
0 \amp 1
\end{bmatrix}
 since this product computes the dot
products between the columns of Q.

statement.p:
Now consider the orthonormal set of vectors

  \uvec_1=\threevec{1/\sqrt{3}}{-1/\sqrt{3}}{1/\sqrt{3}},
  \hspace{24pt}
  \uvec_2=\threevec{1/\sqrt{2}}{1/\sqrt{2}}0,
  \hspace{24pt}
  \uvec_3=\threevec{1/\sqrt{6}}{-1/\sqrt{6}}{-2/\sqrt{6}}

and the matrix they define

  Q = \begin{bmatrix}
  1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{2} \amp 1/\sqrt{6} \\
  -1/\sqrt{3} \amp 1/\sqrt{2} \amp -1/\sqrt{6} \\
  1/\sqrt{3} \amp 0 \amp -2/\sqrt{6} \\
  \end{bmatrix}\text{.}

Here, \uvec_1, \uvec_2, and \uvec_3
form a basis for \real^3 so that both Q^TQ=I_3
and QQ^T=I_3.  Therefore, Q is a square matrix
and is invertible.
